content.heading: Complete Nutritional Guide for Pacman Frogs
content.text: Pacman frogs are obligate carnivores that thrive on variety. In the wild, they ambush prey ranging from insects to small vertebrates. Captive frogs need diverse feeders, proper gutloading, and appropriate supplementation to stay healthy. This guide covers everything from feeder selection to supplement schedules.

rows: As much as eats in 10-15 min

content.text: Safe feeding method: Offer as much as frog eats within 10-15 minutes. This prevents overfeeding and obesity while ensuring adequate nutrition.
AVOID OVERFEEDING - Obesity is extremely common in captive Pacman frogs. Adults need feeding only every 7-10 days. More frequent feeding leads to fatty liver disease and shortened lifespan.
Width of feeder should not exceed the distance between the frog's eyes. Larger feeders risk:

items: Choking or impaction
Regurgitation
Digestive stress
Injury to mouth/throat

content.text: When in doubt, choose smaller feeders. Pacman frogs can eat surprisingly large prey, but err on side of caution.

Goldfish, minnows, white suckers: High thiaminase (breaks down thiamine)
Wild-caught insects: Pesticide risk, parasites, diseases
Wild hornworms: Fed on tomato plants = toxic
Pac Attack / ZooMed Pacman Frog Food: Plant fillers high on ingredients (obligate carnivores)
Beef, pork, chicken: Not balanced nutrition - feed whole prey with bones/organs
Human food: Processed foods, seasonings, etc. are toxic

content.text: Gutloading = feeding insects a nutritious diet 24-48 hours before offering to frog. "You are what you eat" applies - poorly fed insects = poorly fed frog.
Good gutloading foods:

items: Commercial gutload diet (Repashy, Mazuri, Cricket Crack)
Fresh vegetables: collard greens, mustard greens, squash, sweet potato
Fresh fruits: apples, oranges, berries (small amounts)
Whole grains: oats, bran
Bee pollen
Avoid: iceberg lettuce, potatoes, spinach (poor nutrition or calcium blockers)

content.text: Most feeders have more phosphorus than calcium (poor Ca:P ratio). Body needs ~2:1 calcium to phosphorus. Without supplementation, body steals calcium from bones = Metabolic Bone Disease (MBD).
Required supplements:

items: Calcium powder: With D3 if no UVB, without D3 if UVB provided
Multivitamin: With or without D3 depending on UVB setup

content.text: UVB lighting allows frogs to synthesize vitamin D3 in skin to metabolize calcium. If providing UVB, use calcium WITHOUT D3 for most dustings. If NO UVB, use calcium WITH D3.
No UVB = must provide D3 through supplements:
Froglet Schedule (Daily/Every Other Day Feeding):
Pattern: Most feedings get Calcium with D3. Every 3-4 feedings use Multivitamin with D3 instead.
Adult Schedule (Every 7-10 Days):
Pattern: Mostly Calcium with D3, every 3rd-4th feeding is Multivitamin with D3.
UVB provided = use calcium WITHOUT D3 primarily, occasional multivitamin WITH D3:
Froglet Schedule (Daily/Every Other Day Feeding):
Pattern: Most feedings get Calcium (no D3). Every 3-4 feedings use Multivitamin (no D3). Every 7-8 feedings use Multivitamin WITH D3.
Example over 4 weeks:

items: Week 1: Ca, Ca, Ca, MV (no D3)
Week 2: Ca, Ca, Ca, MV WITH D3
Week 3: Ca, Ca, Ca, MV (no D3)
Week 4: Ca, Ca, Ca, MV (no D3)

DO NOT dust rodent or fish feeders with supplements. Whole prey with bones and organs provide complete nutrition already.

content.text: Possible causes:

items: Temperature too low: Warm side must be 80-85°F for proper digestion
New frog stress: Allow 3-7 days to settle in before offering food
Picky eater: Try different feeder types (some frogs have preferences)
Too shy: Some frogs won't eat if watched - leave and check later
Feeding tong fear: Try free-range feeding instead
Wrong feeder size: Too large or too small
Brumation: Some frogs stop eating seasonally (normal if temps stable)
Illness: If refusing food for 2+ weeks with good temps, see vet

content.heading: Problem: Frog keeps begging for food

content.text: Pacman frogs are opportunistic feeders that act hungry constantly. This does NOT mean they need more food:

items: Stick to schedule (adults every 7-10 days)
Overfeeding causes obesity and fatty liver disease
Frog will survive and be healthier on proper schedule
Begging is instinctual, not indication of starvation
Resist temptation to feed early

content.text: MYTH: Hard exoskeletons cause impaction

FALSE. Chitin (exoskeleton material) is a digestible carbohydrate that makes up insect fiber. Hardness does NOT indicate higher fiber. With proper overhead heating providing short wavelength infrared, Pacman frogs easily digest insects with hard exoskeletons. This myth persists despite no scientific evidence.
MYTH: Black soldier fly larvae don't need supplementation

FALSE. While BSFL are very high in calcium, it's mostly in the exoskeleton which some animals can't fully digest. They still need regular calcium and multivitamin supplementation like any other feeder.
MYTH: Feeding live prey is cruel

FALSE. Live prey provides essential behavioral enrichment. Hunting and capturing prey is natural, instinctual behavior. Frozen/thawed options are fine for vertebrate prey (rodents, fish) to avoid aggression injuries, but live insects are appropriate and enriching.
